* {{WP|Natalie Portman}} and {{WP|Jaimie Alexander}} did not reprise their roles as [[Jane Foster (Earth-199999)|Jane Foster]] and [[Sif (Earth-199999)|Lady Sif]], respectively, from the previous two ''Thor'' films.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/creed-star-tessa-thompson-joining-876760|title='Creed' Star Tessa Thompson Joining 'Thor 3'|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=THR|date=11 April 2016|accessdate=11 April 2016}}{{cite|ref=true|url=https://twitter.com/Borys_Kit/status/733724848342634496|title=Not returning to the movie is Jamie Alexander, who plays Sif. Conflict with her BLINDSPOT tv show, according to sources.|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=THR|date=20 May 2016|accessdate=20 May 2016}} Writer [[Eric Pearson]] said that the exclusion of human supporting characters was to give more time to develop Sakaar and Valkyrie.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/1719039/were-the-thor-series-human-characters-ever-in-ragnarok-heres-what-the-writer-told-us|title=Were The Thor Series’ Human Characters Ever In Ragnarok? Here’s What The Writer Told Us|last=Eisenberg|first=Eric|work=CinemaBlend|date=29 October 2017|accessdate=29 October 2017}} Additionally, Alexander claims that Marvel Studios didn't give her enough time to schedule filming around her TV series ''{{WP|Blindspot (TV series)|Blindspot}}''.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/thor-ragnarok-jaimie-alexander-explains-lady-sif-mia-224123524.html|title='Thor: Ragnarok': Jaimie Alexander explains why Lady Sif is MIA|last=Ryder|first=Taryn|work=Yahoo! Entertainment|date=28 October 2017|accessdate=29 October 2017}}
* According to herself, writer Stephany Folsom, who had joined the movie in pre-production to polish the script,{{cite|ref=true|url=http://variety.com/2015/film/news/thor-ragnarok-writer-stephany-folsom-1201652254/|title='Thor: Ragnarok' Taps Screenwriter Stephany Folsom|work=Variety|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=2 December 2015|accessdate=11 September 2017}} was denied a "Story by" credit by the Writers Guild of America due to their regulations, despite Marvel Studios' intention to give her credit.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://twitter.com/StephanyFolsom/status/907375675836817409|title=Stephany Folsom on Twitter: "Marvel gave me "story by"credit on THOR RAGNAROK and the writers' guild denied me the credit due to guild regulations. Are you kidding me?"|last=Folsom|first=Stephany|work=Twitter|date=11 September 2017|accessdate=11 September 2017}}
* A scene from ''Thor: Ragnarok'' depicting Thor meeting Doctor Strange was included as a mid-credits scene in the film ''[[Doctor Strange (film)|Doctor Strange]]''.
* Jeff Goldblum as the Grandmaster made a cameo appearance during the end credits of the film ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2 (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2]]''.
* With a worldwide total box office gross of about $853 million, this film became the 9th-highest-grossing film of 2017.{{cite|ref=true|url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2017&p=.htm|title= 2017 Yearly Box Office Results|work= Box Office Mojo|accessdate= 25 February 2018}}
| Trivia                  = * The song "{{WP|Immigrant Song}}" by {{WP|Led Zeppelin}}, which was used prominently in the film's marketing, was used in the film's first and last action sequences. The song heavily alludes to Norse mythology. Director Taika Waititi believes that using the song in his initial sizzle reel is what got him hired.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/uk/movies/taika-waititi/52768/thor-ragnarok-director-taika-waititi-interview|title=Thor: Ragnarok – director Taika Waititi interview|last=Leane|first=Rob|work=Den of Geek!|date=24 October 2017|accessdate=07 November 2017}}
* The shake weight Skurge uses in the film belongs to Waititi, who bought it while filming ''{{Wc|DC|Green Lantern (Movie)|Green Lantern}}''.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://comicbook.com/marvel/2017/11/03/thor-ragnarok-secret-green-lantern-crossover/|title=How 'Thor: Ragnarok' Had Secret Green Lantern Crossover According To Director|last=Mueller|first=Matthew|work=ComicBook|date=03 November 2017|accessdate=07 November 2017}}
* A preliminary idea had the film take place mostly in [[Valhalla (Afterlife)|Valhalla]]. According to Taika Waititi, that idea "only lasted a couple of weeks."<ref name="Webbed Media">{{cite web|url=https://webbedmedia.com/2018/09/28/taika-waititi-talks-thor-ragnarok/|title=Taika Waititi Talks Thor Ragnarok|work=Webbed Media|date=28 September 2018|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref>
* In the play Loki puts on in Asgard, it is revealed that Loki once turned Thor into a frog. This is a reference to the brief run in comics where Thor was a frog and to the character [[Throg]].
* Thor holding Loki's head in the path of his returning hammer is taken almost directly from a sequence in {{cl|Thor Vol 1 359}}.
* Shady Acres, the destroyed nursing home Odin was residing in, is a nursing home that has appeared in multiple media, most notably on the television series ''{{WP|South Park}}'' and the film ''{{WP|Ace Ventura: Pet Detective}}''.
* While in mortal disguise, Thor's hammer Mjolnir is disguised as an umbrella. Later in the film, Thor taps it on the ground to revert back to wearing his Asgardian armor. This could be an homage to [[Thor Odinson (Earth-616)|his]] early days in the comics, where he'd tap his walking stick on the ground to the same effect.
* Doctor Strange's presence in the movie was decided even before Taika Waititi was brought to direct the film. Before Marvel settled on his role as a minor guest star, Strange was tentatively going to be Thor's partner in his journey, until they decided on the Hulk.<ref name="Webbed Media"/>
* Originally, Thor and Loki find Odin living in the streets of New York. This was changed after test audiences felt his death in that context was too depressing.<ref name="Webbed Media"/>
* In early scripts of the movie, Thor would find that Hela is her sister later on. Waititi opted to "get it out of the way early" in part because he felt it was pointless to try to "compete" with the reveal of {{Wc|starwars|Luke Skywalker|Luke Skywalker}}'s parentage in ''{{Wc|starwars:Star Wars| Episode V The Empire Strikes Back|Star Wars: Episode V - The Empire Strikes Back}}''. He also argued that it was not the most important revelation of the movie, and that it actually helped the plot if Thor knew early on.<ref name="Webbed Media"/>
* The scene of [[Mjolnir]]'s destruction at the hands of [[Hela Odinsdottir (Earth-199999)|Hela]] originally took place in an alleyway in Manhattan, as evidenced by the film's first trailer. For the final cut of the movie, it was changed to an open field in Norway. Waititi explained the setting was changed because he felt the city was a terrible environment for such emotional scene, and additionally to help the pacing of the movie.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/thor/news/a841071/thor-ragnarok-post-credits-sequence-alternate-version/|title=Exclusive: Thor: Ragnarok's post-credits sequence has an alternate version, says director Taika Waititi|work=Digital Spy|first=Rosie|last=Fletcher|date=20 October 2017|accessdate=20 October 2017}}
* Valkyrie actress Tessa Thompson has commented that her character is bisexual.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://screenrant.com/thor-ragnarok-valkyrie-bisexual-tessa-thompson/|title=Thor 3: Tessa Thompson Clarifies Comment on Valkyrie’s Bisexuality|work=Screen Rant|first=Nicholas|last=Raymond|date=25 October 2017|accessdate=1 November 2017}} She also mentioned she had convinced Waititi to shoot a scene with a glimpse of a woman walking out of Valkyrie's bedroom. He kept it in the film as long as he could, but eventually cut it because it distracted from the scene's vital exposition. Thompson also commented that in her mind, one of the members of Valkyrie's warrior clan was her lover.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/features/how-tessa-thompson-went-from-indie-actor-to-thor-ragnarok-badass-w510485|title=How Tessa Thompson Went From Indie Actor to 'Thor: Ragnarok' Badass|work=Rolling Stone|first=Amy|last=Nicholson|date=31 October 2017|accessdate=1 November 2017}}
* Among the statues that commemorate the previous champions of the Grandmaster's contest are the busts of [[Beta Ray Bill]], [[Man-Thing]], [[Ares]], [[Dark-Crawler]] and [[Bi-Beast]].
* A planned Beta Ray Bill cameo was scrapped because Kevin Feige felt it wouldn't do the character justice.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.comicbookmovie.com/thor/thor_ragnarok/thor-ragnarok-heres-why-marvel-decided-to-scrap-beta-ray-bills-planned-cameo-a155018|title=THOR: RAGNAROK: Here's Why Marvel Decided To Scrap Beta Ray Bill's Planned Cameo|work=ComicBookMovie.com|first=Josh|last=Wilding|date=4 November 2017|accessdate=5 November 2017}}
* The song "{{WP|Pure Imagination}}" from ''{{WP|Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory}}'' plays in the background of the scene where Thor is given a background on the Grandmaster. The scene also resembles the trippy boat ride scene from the same film.
* Valkyrie's alias in Sakaar, Scrapper 142, is probably a reference to the character [[Samantha Parrington (Earth-616)|Samantha Parrington]]'s first appearance as Valkyrie in {{cl|Incredible Hulk Vol 1 142}}.
* The Grandmaster's Contest of Champions is named after {{cl|Marvel Super Hero Contest of Champions Vol 1}}, in which [[En Dwi Gast (Earth-616)|the Grandmaster]] plays a key role.
* The film has a few notable callbacks to previous Marvel Cinematic Universe films.
** The "adopted brother" joke from ''[[Marvel's The Avengers]]'' is repeated, but with Loki claiming to be the adopted one this time.
** [[Natalia Romanoff (Earth-199999)|Black Widow's]] "the sun is getting real low" line from ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' is brought up again when Thor tries to calm Hulk down in the arena.
** Hulk smashes Thor on the ground the same way he smashed Loki in ''Marvel's The Avengers''. Loki even revels in watching Thor getting smashed in the same manner.
** Thor's identification code in the Avengers quinjet being "Point Break" is a callback to the nickname [[Anthony Stark (Earth-199999)|Tony Stark]] gave him in ''Marvel's The Avengers''. The nickname itself is a reference to the film ''{{WP|Point Break}}''.
** Bruce failing to turn into the Hulk after jumping out of an aerial vehicle could be a callback to a similar effort made by him in ''[[The Incredible Hulk (2008 film)|The Incredible Hulk]]''.
* According to screenwriter Eric Pearson, Thor's haircut served another purpose in addition to symbolizing Thor's journey, it also prevented Chris Hemsworth from having to wear a wig, which he used to find annoying due to how much time it took to get it right.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.cbr.com/thor-ragnarok-haircut-explained/|title=Why Thor: Ragnarok Gave Marvel's God of Thunder A Haircut|work=CBR.com|first=Stephen|last=Gerding|date=2 November 2017|accessdate=5 November 2017}}
* A rebuilt [[Destroyer (Enchanted Armor)|Destroyer Armor]] was almost featured in the movie, in a scene where it would've tried and miserably failed to stop Hela in Odin's vault. Eric Pearson mentioned the scene was scrapped as it felt unnecessary and slowed down the progress of the story.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.yahoo.com/amphtml/entertainment/big-reveal-nixed-romance-noodle-worm-cut-added-thor-ragnarok-170636900.html|title=The big reveal, the nixed romance, and the noodle worm: What was cut from (and added to) 'Thor: Ragnarok'|work=Yahoo! Entertainment|first=Kevin|last=Polowy|date=10 November 2017|accessdate=15 November 2017}}
* The story about Loki stabbing Thor after disguising himself into a snake was partially improvised. Waititi fed Hemsworth ideas for stories until they settled on the snake story. One of the scrapped versions had Loki shapeshift into a Turkish rug in the middle of a field, prompting Thor to stand on it since he liked them. Loki would then turn back into Loki, revealing a hole in the ground with spikes in the bottom that Thor would have fallen into.<ref name="Webbed Media"/>
* Thor and Loki's "get help" scene wasn't originally in the script. Chris Hemsworth and Tom Hiddlestone came up with it on the day the scene was shot.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.cbr.com/tom-hiddleston-favorite-thor-ragnarok-gag-improv/|title=Tom Hiddleston’s Favorite Thor: Ragnarok Gag Was Pure Improv|work=CBR.com|first=Justin|last=Jones|date=23 October 2018|accessdate=23 October 2018}}
* Before settling on having Bruce Banner fall on his face at the [[Bifrost]], there was going to be a scene of the Revengers landing next to each other. Hulk and Loki would land next to each other, and after a second, Hulk would've punched him out of the frame, mirroring a similar scene between Thor and Hulk during the final battle of ''Marvel's The Avengers''.<ref name="Webbed Media"/>
* A few versions of the movie's plot had Thor prevent Asgard's destruction.<ref name="Webbed Media"/>
* According to himself, for preparation to direct the movie, Taika Waititi only read one Thor comic book, which impulsed him to take the characters to another direction.<ref name="Webbed Media"/>

